{
 "cells": [
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "36953ea9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "# Plotting\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "7bed6ee9",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In this notebook we look at visualizing rhythmic segments. The package does not (currently) provide any plotting functionality. In fact, you hardly need any once you have organized your data in a convenient format. And that is precisely what the package does for you.\n",
    "\n",
    "We will use rhythmic data from Roeske et al. (2020): inter-onset intervals for seperated instruments from a recording of Cuban Salsa & Son music, part of the Interpersonal Entrainment in Music Performance (IEMP) corpus (https://osf.io/37fws/)."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 1,
   "id": "0f77e506",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "array([242.425, 239.653, 439.947, ..., 112.154, 117.026, 287.888],\n",
       "      shape=(38222,))"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 1,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import requests\n",
    "from io import BytesIO\n",
    "import scipy.io\n",
    "\n",
    "# We load the data directly from Mendeley\n",
    "url = \"https://data.mendeley.com/public-files/datasets/s4cjj7h5sv/files/459bd50f-2e6d-43b0-807a-ffde2c126898/file_downloaded\"\n",
    "response = requests.get(url)\n",
    "mat_contents = scipy.io.loadmat(BytesIO(response.content))\n",
    "intervals = mat_contents['CubanSalsa_intervals_ms'].squeeze()\n",
    "intervals"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5629467f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Pattern-duration plot"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "31dab8f7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A pattern-duration plot shows both the pattern and the duration of each segment. For length-2 segments, the pattern can be identified with a single number: the relative duration of the first interval. For example, the segment $(2, 6)$ has pattern $(.25, .75)$ and can be represented using the first number, $0.25$."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "08c2b2a5",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "import numpy as np\n",
    "from rhythmic_segments import RhythmicSegments\n",
    "import matplotlib.pyplot as plt"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "e2c3314b",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "# Extract the segments of length 2, dropping the longest 5%\n",
    "rs = (RhythmicSegments\n",
    "       .from_intervals(intervals, length=2)\n",
    "       .filter_by_duration(max_quantile=.95))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "5a812322",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "Text(0, 0.5, 'Duration (ms)')"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 4,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.scatter(x=rs.patterns[:, 0], y=rs.durations, s=.2, alpha=.1)\n",
    "plt.title('Pattern-duration plot for 2-interval segments')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Pattern (relative duration of first interval)')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Duration (ms)')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "e384b9e0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Alternatively, you can use a hexbin plot to better visualize the density of points:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 5,
   "id": "673003ca",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "Text(0, 0.5, 'Duration (ms)')"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 5,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.hexbin(rs.patterns[:,0], rs.durations, gridsize=(60, 60), cmap='Blues', bins='log')\n",
    "plt.colorbar(label='Segment count')\n",
    "plt.title('Pattern-duration hexbin plot for 2-interval segments')\n",
    "plt.xlabel('Pattern (relative duration of first interval)')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Duration (ms)')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "cff3079b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Phase plot"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "fcc02042",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "A phase plot (see e.g. Ravignani, 2017) shows all segments in a scatter plot, with the first interval on the x-axis and the second interval on the y-axis. This is only possible for length-2 segments."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "7a72e0f2",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "Text(0.5, 1.0, 'Phase plot of 2-interval segments')"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 6,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "plt.scatter(x=rs.segments[:, 0], y=rs.segments[:, 1], s=.1, alpha=.1)\n",
    "plt.xlabel('First interval (ms)')\n",
    "plt.ylabel('Second interval (ms)')\n",
    "plt.title('Phase plot of 2-interval segments')"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "10f8464d",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Triangle plot"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2e53ebf6",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Next, we look at visualizing patterns of length 3:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "5e4ae908",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "rs3 = (RhythmicSegments\n",
    "       .from_intervals(intervals, length=3)\n",
    "       .filter_by_duration(max_quantile=.95))"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "128b696f",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Patterns of length 3 live in a two dimensional simplex, which is a triangular space. \n",
    "We can easily visualize the distribution of length-3 segments using the [matpltern](https://mpltern.readthedocs.io) package."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "507b07fb",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<matplotlib.colorbar.Colorbar at 0x134f36090>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 8,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "import mpltern # noqa: F401\n",
    "from matplotlib.colors import Normalize\n",
    "from mpltern.datasets import get_triangular_grid\n",
    "\n",
    "# Use a linear color map to visualize segment duration\n",
    "cmap = plt.get_cmap('plasma_r')\n",
    "norm = Normalize(vmin=np.min(rs3.durations), vmax=np.max(rs3.durations))\n",
    "colors = cmap(norm(rs3.durations))\n",
    "\n",
    "# Scatterplot in ternary plot\n",
    "ax = plt.subplot(projection=\"ternary\")\n",
    "top, left, right = rs3.patterns.T\n",
    "ax.scatter(top, left, right, c=colors, s=.02, alpha=.5)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Add triangular grid\n",
    "ax.triplot(*get_triangular_grid(8), 'k-', lw=.5, alpha=0.3)\n",
    "\n",
    "# Show colorbar\n",
    "sm = plt.cm.ScalarMappable(cmap=cmap, norm=norm)\n",
    "sm.set_array([])  # Needed for colorbar to work\n",
    "plt.colorbar(sm, ax=ax, label='Duration (ms)', pad=0.1)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "95536bf0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Alternatively, you can use a tribin (or hexbin) plot to visualize density of segments in pattern space, but then you cannot visualize duration at the same time."
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "d591f000",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<matplotlib.collections.PolyCollection at 0x133df1010>"
      ]
     },
     "execution_count": 9,
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "execute_result"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 640x480 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "ax = plt.subplot(projection=\"ternary\")\n",
    "top, left, right = rs3.patterns.T\n",
    "ax.tribin(top, left, right, bins=\"log\", cmap=\"plasma_r\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "5585e1cf",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## References\n",
    "\n",
    "Ravignani, A. (2017). Visualizing and Interpreting Rhythmic Patterns Using Phase Space Plots. Music Perception, 35(5), 557–568. https://doi.org/10.1525/mp.2017.34.5.557\n",
    "\n",
    "Roeske, Tina; Jacoby, Nori (2020), “Musical rhythm: Onsets/intervals of seven music corpora”, Mendeley Data, V2, https://doi.org/10.17632/s4cjj7h5sv.2\n",
    "\n",
    "Roeske, T. C., Tchernichovski, O., Poeppel, D., & Jacoby, N. (2020). Categorical Rhythms Are Shared between Songbirds and Humans. Current Biology, 30(18), P3544-3555.e6. https://doi.org/10.1016/j.cub.2020.06.072\n",
    "\n"
   ]
  },
